column168: On 12/05/2020 at 0838 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Sumter Yard (Sumter, SC) discovered  GATX9327, a loaded tank car of Compressed gas, Flammable, N.O.S (Isobutylene, Xylene) leaking  from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, SI Group was notified.  Marion Environmental Inc (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, responded and found the liquid line a quarter turn open and the secondary closure plug a full turn loose. The issue was identified and  corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, SI Group (Ryan Washburn 518-347-4528).  MEI tightened the liquid line and tightened the secondary closure plug.  The car was released into  transportation.
column169: (nar cause code: 119 5 What Failed: Liquid Line / Liquid Valve Where Failed: Closure plug Why Failed: Less than tool tight, valve open)

On 12/1/2020 at 1100 ET, approximately 5 gallons of UN1791, Hypochlorite Solution with more than 5% but less than 16% available chlorine, 8, PGIII was discovered on the trailer floor when seven (7) empty totes with residual product were unloaded. It was confirmed that the totes were loaded upside down and the caps came loose in transit resulting in the release of approximately 5 gallons. Environmental Hazmat Services (EHS) was dispatched to decontaminate the impacted trailer floor. Sodium bicarbonate was utilized to neutralize the trailer floor. The area was then cleaned with simple green to reduce the odor. The spent neutralizer, absorbents and debris were placed into one (1) 5 - gallon poly drum. The contractor then departed the site with the waste generated.

column168: At 1437 ET, XPO contacted ERTS regarding a trailer that was leaking while traveling. The trailer was located at the Allsups, 402 O'Brien St, Wickett, TX 79788. At 1445 ET, ERTS contacted Allied International Emergency for a response. At 1709 ET, contractors arrived onsite and confirmed the release was from a 5 gallon plastic jug of Jet Ag - Fungicide due to being punctured by a nail in the pallet. Contractors confirmed the release was less than one gallon impacting a 1' by 1' area inside the trailer and a 1' by 10' area on the asphalt outside the trailer. The trailer was offloaded and cleaned. Contractors confirmed they will make sure there are no more nails sticking out of the pallet prior to restacking the pallet. column168: On 12/09/2020, at 1851 hours, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Terminal Mechanical Department discovered PROX 32116, a residue tank car of Petroleum Gases (Propylene), leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and National Response Center, Ohio EPA, and Federal Railroad Administration were notified. The emergency response telephone number on the waybill was contacted,  (CHEMTREC Report #2020-1215-00163), and as of this report no successful notification to the shipper of record has been made despite multiple attempts. Joseph Taylor, a CSXT Senior Manager of Hazardous Materials was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve 1/8 turn in the open position and the vapor valve secondary closure plug was not installed resulting in a vapor release of lading. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the FRA, as the shipper has been unreachable. Mr. Taylor closed the valve, installed the secondary closure plug, thus securing the release. The car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required?  Cause Code: 136 NARRI: 90

column168: The owner of the facility showed our driver where the tank was.  He told our driver there was enough capacity as it was a 5000 gallon tank.  Our driver didn't validate how much was in it or what the bill of lading showed 5100 gallons and our work assignment showed 4731 gallons.  He felt he should trust the owner.  He could readily tell us what the Schneider process is which is to go by capacity minus 10% for the stopping point.  Before the first spill happened he realized it wasn't going to all fit and he walked to tell the customer that which was over 100 feet away and up on a ledge inside a building.  The owner said they were currently at 4500 gallons and to go shut down.  Before the driver could get back to the truck product started overflowing.  He knew the process is we shut down product flow when leaving the controls but did not do that here.  We also learned he was utilizing 25psi and again commented that he knew Schneider policy is 15psi or less except with approval for special situations.  Approximately 5 gallons spill initially.  They then went to a second storage tank where the customer advised it would hold the rest.  He told the driver to drape the hose over in to the tank.  Nothing was securing the hose.  This is another violation of Schneider policy.  We must always have a secure connection.  The driver stilll had 25psi on the trailer and opened the valve.  The resulting force caused the hose to come out of the customer tank spilling an estimated 25 gallons extra.  It was contained inside of their building, same place where the other spill occurred.
column169: There were many things that went wrong on this delivery.   • Capacity validation • Too much air pressure  • Valves fully open at the end of filling • Walking away with product flowing • Unsecure connection The fact that our driver could recite most of the processes he should have been following but chose not to is decidedly a behavioral issue.  In our experience that is hard to correct or change in someone so we severed employment ties with this individual.  We have also provided feedback to the customer that we should always validate starting amounts in tanks, as well as what is being delivered, and always using secure connections.

column161: LISA MARTIN ON BEHALF OF HERITAGE TRANSPORT
column168: Description of Events & Package Failure: While unloading a shipment being received on December 3, 2020, a Heritage Environmental Services, LLC (“Heritage”) employee discovered two totes leaking from uncapped valves.  The totes contained RQ,UN3264,WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S.,8,PGII,(PHOSPHORIC ACID, NITRIC ACID),(D002),ERG#154.  It is estimated that less than 1 liter of material combined had leaked onto the trailer floor from both totes.  The material did not get outside of the trailer.  Heritage personnel immediately placed caps on the bottom valves of the totes and cleaned up the spilled material.  Response time for cleanup was approximately 30 minutes.  Heritage personnel acted appropriately and promptly in accordance with the facility’s Contingency Plan to contain the material.  Material Involved in Incident: Approximately one liter of waste phosphoric acid/nitric acid was released, identified on line 1 of manifest 001078741WAS, RQ,UN3264,WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S.,8,PGII,(PHOSPHORIC ACID, NITRIC ACID),(D002),ERG#154.  Heritage Transport had possession of this material as it was being unloaded at the Part B Permitted Treatment, Storage and Disposal Facility located at Heritage Environmental Services, 8525 NE 38th Street, Kansas City, Missouri.  Approximately 20 pounds of clay absorbent was recovered and placed into 5-gallon container for proper disposal.
column169: Recommendations/Actions Taken to Prevent Recurrence:  Based on the incident review, caps should have been in-place on the bottom valves of the totes prior to offering for transportation.  Heritage notified the generator/offeror of the material involved in this incident.  The offeror assured Heritage that containers will be inspected for proper closure prior to offering for transportation in order to prevent future recurrence.

column168: On December 28, 2020 at 1648 ET, Jeff Lewis with MC Tank Transport contacted ERTS regarding a leaking tank at a truck was located at 4124 E Hwy 30, St Gabriel, LA 70776. It was advised that the tank is leaking from the bottom driver axel. The product freezes and is frozen on the parts of the truck and a small amount has impacted the asphalt below. ERTS has dispatched an environmental contractor to perform a product transfer. Site personnel have release point secured and are collecting the released product in a pail. The environmental contractor arrived on site and performed a product transfer into a 2nd CTMV. The contractor reported that transfer operations are completed. The contractor supvr estimated that approximately 1 gallon released to the body of the tanker and approximately 6 oz was collected in the containment pool. The contractor supvr advised the tanker is leaking somewhere under the insulation around the area of the internal valve. The contractor supvr stated that the tanker was moved over to the site wash bay. No other waste was generated.

column168: Driver was in transit transporting a liquid load with a tractor and tanker combination. Driver was initiating a left hand turn at an intersection to get on the entrance ramp to the interstate. While negotiating the turn the liquid movement inside the tanker moved to the right and caused the truck and tanker to roll over onto its right side. There was more liquid movement due to the 7000 gallon tanker being loaded with approximately 3500 gallons. No other vehicles were involved in the accident. After the rollover occurred it was discovered that there was a small leak from one of the wash out caps on top of the tanker. The police department and fire department responded to the scene. The fire department contained the spill. An emergency response crew was also engaged to respond to the scene for clean up and remediation. The truck was up-righted and the load was transloaded to another tanker for delivery. The spill clean up, remediation and disposal have been completed.

On 12/13/2020 This shipment was discovered during the physical inspection process at the DHL IAH Service Center, located at 18705 Lee Road, Ste 500, Humble, TX 77338, to contain hidden dangerous goods. Transportation by road has been confirmed.

On 12/02/2020, at approximately 08:30 Employee # 6233804 called to report a product spill and suspected that it was a potential undeclared dangerous goods shipment. Per the agent, the lid came off 1 of the 2 plastic bottles, causing the contents to leak all over inside of the box and outside of box. other plastic bottle containing same epoxy was not damaged. An SDS online revealed that the commodity is classified as hazardous material. The shipment did not have the required markings, labeling, packaging or paperwork in compliance with the IATA Regulations, thus deeming this shipment as an undeclared dangerous goods shipment. The package is being held for an investigation from the FAA.

On 12/30/2020 at 0912 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Maxwell Yard (Greenwood, SC) discovered  PROX71104, a loaded tank car of Ethylene Glycol leaking from top of the car after the tank car was  involved in a derailment and was leaning at a angle. The car was isolated and the shipper, Shell  Chemicals Canada was notified. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found that the  tank car had been leaking from the liquid line but the leak had since stopped.. The issue was identified  and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Shell Chemicals Canada  (Greg Hallet 403-606-8436) Greg.Hallet@Shell.com. HEPACO monitored the tank car during the  rerailing and did not observe the tank car leak..  The car is on hold pending sampling of the product   coordinated by the shipper.

On December 7, 2020, at 1100 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the Conrail Pavonia Terminal, Camden, New Jersey  reported that an NJ DOT Hazardous Material Inspector took exception to SHPX 201626, a Residue last contained  tank car of UN1090, Acetone. Reportedly, there was hissing escaping from around the manway and the smell of  Acetone atop the tank car. The tank car was isolated from Yard employees. The shipper, Chemisphere, Corporation  was notified via Chemtrec, report #2020-12-07-00091. Marion Environmental Inc. a Conrail emergency response  contractor, was dispatched to the Pavonia Terminal as well as Joseph Caccamo, Manager of Hazardous Material for  Conrail. It was found that the manway was releasing a slight amount of vapor from around the seal. All manway  securement bolts were found tight however after inspection of the manway ring gasket it was determined that the  gasket was in poor condition with an area crushed and heavily grooved beyond specification. A new nozzle gasket  was installed on the manway and it was secured properly. The tank car was then released for disposition.   NARRI: 5x(4+3+0)x(2+0) = 70 Cause code: 209

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: On 12/8/2020 a steel 55 gallon drum (551A1) was identified as leaking upol arrival at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY transportation terminal. Upon inspection it was determined that there was a small crack in the drum on the bottom of the container. The drum was overpacked into a 85 gallon steel drum to continue transportation to the treatment storage and disposal facility.    The drum leaked less than 1 pint of mixed solvents while in transit due to the crack. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the drum was over-packed into an appropriate salvage drum. The duration of release is anticipated to be a small drip from the drum for about 24 hours.
column169: On 12/8/2020 the Veolia safety manager of Schenectady, NY was notified. The results of the investigation is that a drum either had a small hole or crack in it from the manufacturer or the crack or hole was caused when moving the drum with a drum cart. It is hard to determine the exact cause of spill as it was a very small hole/crack and was only slightly dripping when discovered.  Veolia employees must continue to inspect drums when handling prior to and during transportation and notify management upon discovery of a leaking container. Veolia will continue to review the causes of spills with employees.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On December 30, 2020, at 0700 hours, a Transportation Manager at the Conrail Pavonia Terminal, Camden,  New Jersey reported that SOTX 1271, a loaded tank car of UN1268, Petroleum Distillates N.O.S. (GASOLINE)   was leaking from the top of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper SMS Rail, Brian Murray  609-868-3089  was notified directly by Conrail. SMS Rail informed that the responsible party was actually  SAMUEL CORALUZZO CO INC, Chris Lownes 609-970-7250. Marion Environmental Inc. a Conrail response contractor,  was dispatched to the Terminal and found that the release was from an improperly secured hinged and bolted  manway. Eight of eight manway securement bolts were found less than tool tight. The manway gasket was  inspected and found in proper condition so the manway was then properly secured. All other fittings were inspected  with no other exceptions found. Once the tank car was properly secured it was then released for transportation.  NARRI: 5x(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 80 Cause code: 200

column168: As an employee was completing transfer of material from the rail tanker to the tank truck, the hose was being emptied. The employee removed the hose from the valve assembly on the rail tanker and placed it over the railing, but did not tie the hose off to the railing of the tanker prior to moving on to the next step in the task. The hose slipped from the railing and fell to the ground, spilling approximately 24 gallons of material to the ground in the RTF East Building.    The duration of the spill, from the time it occurred until cleanup was completed, was approximately 15 minutes. The spilled material was immediately diked up to keep it from spreading and was then absorbed with floor dry.
column169: USEI has reviewed the work standard and found that it is inadequate. The work standard will be updated to include securing the hose after it has been removed from the rail tanker valve so that there is no possibility for it to fall to the ground and allow residual material to escape.

AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED AND THE SPILLAGE CLEANED UP, THEN ALL MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS A MINISCULE PUNCTURE HOLE AT THE BOTTOM CORNER OF THE CONTAINER. THERE WAS NO OUTER CARTON/CONTAINMENT.
PACKAGE LEAKING 1.4C EXPLOSIVE WAS FOUND ON CART IN DMP. ALL PROCESSES FOLLOWED, CHAIN OF COMMAND, NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL SPILL COORDINATOR AND CHSP SAFETY COORDINATOR
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: A trailer transporting 1,560 commercial size propane cylinders (4.5 gallon capacity) was discovered leaking at a DOT weigh station. The shipper recovered the questionable cylinders and transported them offsite.

column168: Upon arrival at the destination terminal, the tote was discovered leaking inside the trailer. Investigation revealed that a sharp piece of freight shifted and punctured the tote. column169: Had additional dunnage been placed around the tote or the other freight been more adequately blocked and braced, this incident may not have occurred. This incident may be used in future safety meetings to illustrate the importance of properly blocking and bracing freight for transit.

column168: TILX 362019 was involved in a derailment during which the manway cover was impacted.  The manway cover was broken from the impact, allowing a section to be separated from the rest of the cover and releasing 250-500 gallons (est) of product to Deer Creek.

While cargo tank was being loaded, the driver was distracted and not paying attention to the gauges. Once the product filled the cargo tank it entered the vent pipe and out onto the ground. The spilled product covered an area of approximately 4 ft. by 200 yards. The driver shut off the pump and closed the valves. Company personnel responded and called a third party hazmat clean up crew. Michigan DEQ came to the site as well. Puddled product was vacuumed up. Impacted soil was excavated clean in accordance with Michigan DEQ requirements and removed from the site for disposal. New soil and grass seed was put in.
column169: Responsible driver completed remedial training and evaluation on loading/unloading procedures. The cause of the spill was, distraction and inattention was reviewed with all company drivers in safety meetings to prevent reoccurrence.

column168: On 12/24/2020 at 0230 ET, a fuel overfill occurred at the referenced location, a Circle K gas station when National Petroleum Trucking was offloading diesel fuel. As a result, approximately 100 gallons of diesel fuel released impacting a 60' by 100' area of the concrete parking lot. Hulcher Services was dispatched to the site to perform cleanup activities. The contractor applied granular absorbents to impacted area of concrete to absorb and solidify the released diesel fuel. The spent absorbents were then collected and containerized into three (3) 55 - gallon metal drums. Hulcher Services then departed the site with the waste generated.   On 1/10/21, Hulcher Services transported the three (3) 55 - gallon metal drums containing non - hazardous, diesel impacted absorbents to Turkey Creek Landfill located in Alvarado, TX for disposal.

column168: The  Hilco Transport Company vehicle was traveling Westbound on US Highway 64. A large plastic container (flower pot) fell from a third party vehicle in front of the Hilco vehicle. The driver of the Hilco Vehicle swerved to the in an attempt to avoid the container.  The rear tandem axles of the cargo trailer left the roadway into the highway median.  This caused the tractor trailer driver to lose control. The vehicle entered the highway median and overturned just East of the intersection of US Highway 64 and Bob Horton Road. The body of the tanker was damaged resulting in the release of approximately 700 gallons of aviation gasoline, with the release occurring over an estimated three hour period. The damage to the tanker body consisted of a three foot long crack near the bottom center of the tanker. Remaining fuel in the tanker was off-loaded into another Hilco tanker.

column168: Our driver was parked and delivering gasoline when another motorist drove through our safety cones  into our driver's work area. The spill itself was a result of damage to the delivery hose by a motorist  while the driver was offloading gasoline into the site's UST. Approximately 150 gallons of regular  gasoline was released when the motorist drove over said delivery hose, damaging the drop valve and causing the release. Local Fire Department and Law Enforcement were on site to cordon  off the dispenser area where the spill occurred until an emergency response crew could be called out  to the site. No storm drains were observed to have been impacted in the area.
column169: This spill was a result of another motorist. This was not our driver's fault.

column168: As per the NYPD prepared motor vehicle report, when our vehicle rolled onto its side on top of the guard rail, the diesel fuel tank ruptured and propane cylinders that had come loose ignited due to a source of ignition which, most likely, was the ruptured diesel fuel tank. Due to the nature of propane, the heat from the diesel tank fire served to raise the level of PSI within many of the 20# cylinders and their relief valves opened, venting propane which ignited and sent a number of cylinders flying in many directions. The relief valves did NOT fail- they operated as prescribed. By the time the fire department arrived and subdued the fire, most of the cylinders remained intact as their surface area was cooled by the air temperature and water. The release lasted about 45 minutes until the fire department get the situation under control. The fire was intense althe beginning of the event and was extinguished by the NYCFD.
column169: Clearly this was a direct result of the improper actions of the other driver that occured when the two lanes narrowed into one; the other driver then raced in front of our truck, causing our driver to swerve to aviod a serious collision. We did sit with our driver after the event. He was operating a high center-of-gravity rack truck and re-educated him about the danger of tyving with a fully loaded truck. No other action was taken.

column169: ONCE OUR DRIVER WAS EXAMINED BY MEDICAL PERSONELL THEY DETERMINED THAT THIS DRIVER HAD A SERIES OF STROKES. AS FAR AS RECOMMENDATIONS DO, I THINK COMPANIES SHOULD REQUIRE REST BREAKS AFTER 3-4 HOURS OF DRIVING WE PAY OUR DRIVERS BY THE HOUR INSTEAD OF BY THE MILE WITH THE GOAL OF SLOWING THE DRIVERS BY THE HOUR INSTEAD OF BY THE MILE WITH THE GOAL OF SLOWING THE DRIVERS DOWN AND DECREASING ACCIDENTS AND OTHER POOR DRIVING BEHAVIOR , I BELIEVE ALL TRUCKING COMPANIES SHOULD DO THE SAME.

column168: This is a revision to previously submitted 5800 # 4000071352, due to corrected shipper and commodity information.  We further examined the matter and again did the physical inspection of the spilled package (01) staged at Chatrapati Shivaji Maharaj International Airport, Mumbai. The inspection was conducted by the teams comprising FEDEX Health & Safety, Operations and MIAL representative . During the physical inspection of the DG spilled package, we found the paperwork relating to DG shipment vide Air Waybill No. 165924174750 ( the DG shipment) and it was identified that the leaked commodity was Class 3 commodity, UN 1993 Flammable Liquid N.O.S. ( Kerosine, Petroleum, Hydrodesulphurized) of Packing Group III (Low risk) .  The shipment containing 2 boxes belonging to the shipper , Allied Packaging, situated at SHOP NO..2 Dhumal EST NR SAI NAGAR & RES , ASALPHA , GHATKOPAR W, MUMBAI 400086 was booked vide air Waybill No. 1659 2417 4750 under MAWB NO. 023 6693 7253 for the consignee, Aidani Global Traders, based at SUIT NO 3 A-33, BLOCK B2 LEISURE COMMERCE SQUARE JALAN, PJS 8/9, 46150 PETALING JAYA , BELNGOR DARUL EHASAN, SELANGOR, MALAYSIA. THE DG shipment was handed over to FEDEX on December XX, 2020 by the agent Citi Network Logistics P Ltd. after customs clearance for and on behalf of the shipper.

On December 18, 2020, at approximately 9:25 a.m. CST, one(1) 5-gallon pail of UN3266 corrosive liquid(sodium hydroxide) was punctured by a forklift at the above-referenced R+L Carriers(RLC) location. As a result of the puncture, approximately five(5) gallons of product released to the concrete surface. RLC personnel deployed granular absorbents to the release. At approximately 10:28 a.m. CST, a representative from RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CEIS) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Advanced Environmental Solutions(AES) to assess the site and perform the necessary corrective action. Following a site assessment, AES personnel determined no additional absorbents were necessary to remediate the impacted surface. All previously spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one(1) 55-gallon for transport and disposal. AES secured the site and demobilized, noting no further actions required.

column168: During PM sort operations at the OKCA FedEx Express origin station in Oklahoma City, OK a fibreboard box associated with tracking number 772369622504 was observed leaking. The package was offered for shipment from the United States to Akure, Nigeria. Upon further inspection the box contained power equipment, and labeling on the box identified the equipment as a PowerStroke 3100 PSI Pressure Washer Model No ZRPS803188 that was reconditioned. Staff at the origin station noted liquid staining the bottom of the package that had the odor of gasoline. There were no dangerous goods markings or labels on the package and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. A Commercial invoice offered with the package listed the Description of Goods as PERSONAL USE PACKAGE. The station was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff hold the shipment pending further disposition instruction.

column168: Two fiberboard boxes, each containing one inner metal can or paint and four inner plastic bottles of primer were observed leaking during PM sort operations at the FedEx Express hub in Memphis, TN. The packages were part of a two piece MPS shipment. The master tracking number was 187817323343, and it was leaking a small amount from one of the bottles of primer. The other package was associated with tracking number 187817323354 and a small amount of paint leaked from the inner can in that package. The shipment had been declared to contain dangerous goods by the shipper and a Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. The commodities were listed as UN1263 Paint. FedEx Spill Cleanup staff reported that the package had been dropped while handling it during the fort. Spill Cleanup staff at the hub were directed by· Dangerous. Goods Administration*to contain the shipment and hold the packages pending further disposition instruction. An Amended Shippers Declaration was subsequently received from the shipper, and the packages were dispositioned for final delivery to the consignee.

SequenceEvent: At 5:00 pm a package handler was emptying vehicle 439394 and could hear sizzling coming from the van. Alex evacuated the area of package handlers and with the help of senior admin Ed Day, removed the hazmat from the vehicle in the appropriate red receptacles, and moved the vehicle outside of the building. Following the directions in the emergency response guidebook, Ed used kitty liter to absorb the corrosive liquid spill. DescribePack: The hazmat was tipped on its side on the floor of the vehicle underneath the shelf on the driver side. There were four 1 gallon jugs in the box, one was noticeably leaking, it an estimated 2 liters of liquid. The top of the bottle by the cap was caved in. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Once the spill was discovered, the bottles were placed in the red bin receptacles where hazmat damages are stored. The van was then moved outside of the building and kitty litter was placed on the spill to prevent further spread.

SequenceEvent: a 5 gallon collapsible plastic jug with a simple screw-on cap was placed in a fiberboard box and shipped.  at some point during transit the screw-on cap loosened and a small amount of the jug's contents leaked.  the leakage was absorbed by the outer pkg and had mostly dried by the time of inspection. the outer pkg displayed hazardous materials labeling and the appearance of the area that had been damp suggested that a corrosive liquid was probable. inspection revealed that the box was glued closed except for a portion of the pkg's top which had been pulled open and taped to re-close.  it is possible that the top was opened, the cap was tightened, and the box re-closed and forwarded.  the jug's cap was tight and not leaking at the time of inspection but there were small moisture droplets about the cap. DescribePack: threaded caps loosen from the vibration of transit. it is the probable cause of failure in this incident. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: the pkg was not sent out for delivery after reaching the destination station.

On December 7,2020, personnel at the R+L Carriers(RLC) terminal located at the above-referenced address observed a cargo leak in trailer T55654 docked at door 259. Upon further inspection, one(1) 1-gallon container of UN1987 alcohols and one(1) 5-gallon container of 10% neutral buffered formalin were damaged and released approximately one(1) gallon of UN1987 alcohols and five(5) gallons of 10% neutral buffered formalin to the trailer interior. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services(HES) to perform the necessary corrective action. Crew members deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer surfaces and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents and the damaged containers were collected and containerized into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. Crews secured the scene and demobilized, no further actions required.

On 12/24/2021, at approximately 08:15, Dangerous goods Administration received a call from Spill Agent# 472483 at the ORF station, reporting a potential undeclared dangerous goods shipment. Upon inspection, the package contained 6 plastic bottles of hand sanitizer, each incased in a wooden dispenser box. The 6 wooden boxes were packed in a large cardboard box. Per the Agent, all 6 containers leaked from the top of the dispenser spout. It was reported that the spouts were not covered nor did they have a locking mechanism to prevent unintentional dispensing. The percentage of alcohol content is unknown, as there are no markings or paperwork provided with this information. The shipment was placed in a steel salvage package and are being held for investigation by the FAA.

column168: On 12/31/2020 at 9:58 AM, the Kansas City Southern Railway's(KCS) Environmental& Hazmat Department was notified that an odor was emanating from GLNX 23255, load of Flammable Liquids NOS//Crude Sulfate Turpentine, while located at the KCS Shreveport, LA rail yard. Residue on top of the car was also reported. Environmental& Hazmat mobilized a railroad qualified response contractor to investigate the report. Upon arrival, the response contractor discovered 8 of 8 manway securement bolts less than tool tight, and the manway cover gasket in poor condition, causing Ieakage while traveling. A new manway rim nozzle gasket was installed and the manway securement bolts tightened tool tight. All other tank car closures were checked and verified to be tool tight. Once secure, the car was returned to transportation. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
